I'm a pilot... and the analogy to the autonomous flying has some merit but also has some big flaws.  In any weather (good or bad) the computer or the pilot are using instruments to provide positional information that you cannot get from simply looking out the window.  And though the "computer" is flying the pilots still "tweak" settings to fine tune how well the computer flies in real time.  Also, there are massive systems on the ground to provide the situational precision required to work.  The planes cannot just automatically land on any long strip of ground.  There is as much work going on on the ground to get the plan to land correctly as there is happening in the plane.  The planes line up with the landing systems on the ground and together the whole thing works. But planes don't have dozens of other planes just a few feet away from them moving is different direction, stopping and starting, swerving, failing to stop when they should... you get the pictures.  Planes operate in an extremely controlled environment with humans keeping them separated typically by miles not feet.  Cars operate in a much more complex environment with many more possibilities.  I have a Tesla with FSD and it's amazing.  These systems will get there but it will probably take all cars talking to each other and working together to do this nearly as safely as planes do it.  The biggest difference, I believe, is humans can anticipate... they can intuit what other drivers are about to do and prepare a response before something happens.  Not perfectly or all the time of course and drivers that aren't paying attention or are impaired can't do that... but computer can only really react.  They can react very quickly, faster than a human, but they don't anticipate like humans and so you get strange (non-human) reactions. Like slamming on the brakes in a strange way.  Right now the number of cars on the road attempting to drive themselves is so tiny and other human drivers can react to the strange times they make very weird mistakes that it's not leading to major problems... yet.  Also driving around Phoenix is not nearly as challenging as driving around let's say, Los Angeles or Manhattan.  It's the edge cases where these systems are 10+ years away from reality.  On wide, well marked streets in suburban Phoenix these systems do okay but there is a long way to go before you should really want driverless cars on the road.

Waymo will win on short run, but will loose on long one. This is why even after all these years Waymo is still limited to small areas in just a handful cities , because it simply doesn't scale...

It‚Äôs actually pretty easy to prevent remote hacking of cars. They are not general purpose computers, nor web surfing machines. In fact, the infotainment system on every car in existence is already completely separate from the CANBUS network of microcontrollers that actually drive your car

If they weren‚Äôt, then a crash of your CarPlay or Tesla touchscreen would suddenly cause your car to be uncontrollable and potentially crash

Fortunately, that‚Äôs not how these things work. I can literally reboot the touchscreen in my Tesla while on AutoPilot, and the self-driving computer and CANBUS microcontrollers couldn‚Äôt care less

The funny thing is, we are reaching the point where humans no longer write the software

The neural nets used by Tesla literally train themselves. The vast number of variables involved in computer vision and being able to understand the world around the car is far too large to be hand coded by anyone

Yes, they currently have C code running on top of the AI, in order to provide software for things that the neural nets have not learned yet. But in the long run, the entire self-driving stack will just be a group of highly tuned neural nets that 1) can generate a 3D vector-space representation of the world (from 8 cameras with 2D images), 2) can create a plan for maneuvering in that environment to get where the user wants to go, and 3) can manipulate the steering, pedals, and signals with perfect timing to achieve the plan

I totally agree that cars should go fully autonomous. Even better, we humans should not even be allowed to drive cars, we are dangerous.

As for Waymo, no, it is not fully autonomous it can't even be considered level 4, it can't think for itself, and it certainly can't predict what others may do. 
Also, it only works on geofenced pre-maped locations that act as "invisible rails" because the car can't understand what is happening around it, it will need machine learning A.I. to do that, while Waymo uses mostly human-writen code.
I could put a few cameras on a car and hard-code it to work around my neighborhood without a driver, this would not make it a fully autonomous car (meaning level 5). This is exactly what Waymo does but on a larger scale because of budget.

Waymo is 6-8 years behind Tesla and will probably never have anything better than lvl 3 that will work out of the specified locations as long as they keep using Lidar and not a vision-only/focused approach with machine learning and a huge amount of data (which they lack) to train it. 

Tesla will have level 5 by the end of 2023 and it will work everywhere, while Waymo will continue to only work on few pre-maped locations. The most important reason for this colossal lead is their approach (vision-based vs lidar), and the second reason is the amount and quality of the data. 
Waymo's number and quality are a joke, Tesla has more than 3.5 BILLION miles (at least 100 times of what Waymo has) on its A.I. and they also have more "real-world" conditions because they are not in few specified locations that are easy to drive around.

What this video does not make clear and I know first hand as a 13-year resident of Chandler Arizona, is that these vehicles are operating in an exceptionally limited context. The eastern boundary of the service area along McQueen road has not moved in years. For all the miles they claim logged, they are covering the same roads over and over, using a substantial sensor array. In all that time, I have not seen a single van run around without a driver. This video is the very first instance and I have spent substantial time near the Waymo depot in addition to watching them drive around my city for years.

On the other hand, I've rented a Tesla model S with FSD beta enabled for an entire week and used that to drive around the northern Virginia area. I was more attentive in the waymo vehicle because I knew I had zero ability to get involved aside from asking the vehicle to stop where the Tesla actually allowed me to relax a bit more with the knowledge I still could take over if I had the need. Considering the costs I've seen so far, waymo would make no sense unless you were writing it infrequently and unless their team pulls out the secret weapon I would pull out (George and Elon were both right and yet missed the bigger picture), it's hard to imagine Waymo being able to provide service over enough area to ever be relevant, especially when compared to what Tesla is already capable of doing with their continuously growing fleet of vehicles, all around the world.

A driverless car would be ideal for my visually impaired girlfriend as it would solve her problem of short distance to medium distance travel. A lot of her time is wasted going to the start point of public transport, switching public transport and from end point to final destination. However, this technology is only viable if it's truly autonomous 100% of the time. That means not only must it be able to navigate all kinds of obstacles like roadworks and accidents, but also all kinds of weather. (Rain still seems to be a problem for Waymo sensory systems.) A lot of road infrastructure has to be either changed or augmented to accommodate these vehicles. For example traffic regulatory systems (traffic lights, speed signs, etc) need some way of communicating with the vehicle as well as communication between vehicles. Also for better or worse a lot of legislation has to be done. (It took literally centuries to come up with road rules.) And we as a society have to accept that small and major accidents will happen. I also imagine that "car ownership" is going to be an issue. It looks that Tesla bets that cars will be still owned by the majority of individuals, while the rest (Alphabet, Ford, etc) assumes that a "car as a service" is the more likely outcome. I can imagine that we might not even have individual cars in the future, but something that is a hybrid between car, bus and train.
So from an engineering point of view I understand your enthusiasm. In the end it's not the engineering but timing and luck which determines the success of autonomous vehicles.

An exception for planes is strong crosswinds, where humans are thought to be better at compensating. (I‚Äôm not entirely sure if they really are, but that seems to be what most pilots think.)

Of course planes can auto land in bad visibility because the airport is fully equipped with special radio-wave landing assistance systems that help tell the plane whether it‚Äôs on the right path, without the plane needing to use any of its own sensors to otherwise detect the runway and without needing any optical measurements. Also, runways are always straight and flat and it is always a pretty good assumption that they are clear of any obstacles. 

No roads are so equipped to help tell a car where it is, nor are they straight, flat, or clear of obstacles. So cars have to rely entirely on their own optical and other sensors to determine their position, where the road is going, the state of traffic signals or other signage, and where various unpredictably moving obstacles are (or will soon be going). It does not seem obvious that they would NECESSARILY be much better than a human at this in bad weather/visibility, especially when eschewing the use of non-optical sensors, as in the case of Tesla. Having non-optical distance sensors that can cut through fog, or see as well in the dark as they do in daylight, or monitor 360 degrees simultaneously, are a big advantage though. But they could also be used to provide an enhanced display for human drivers.

I wrote a paper in July 2018 titled, "What is society's understanding of the impact/benefits of autonomous vehicles?"
In 2020 there was 1.37 fatalities per 100 million vehicle miles traveled by humans. That translates to about 100 people per day, or 36,000+ people per year.
When I wrote the paper in 2018, there had been a total of 4 fatalities with autonomous vehicles in the USA (3 by Tesla and 1 by Uber) with over 5 billion autonomous miles driven. That makes 0.08 fatalities per 100,000,000 miles driven.

*Deaths per 100,000,000 miles driven:*
Humans: 1.37 (36,000+ deaths a year)
Autonomous driving: 0.08 (4 deaths total)

You pick which one you think is safer. ;) I'll hard pressed to give up driving, because, well, I love it. But the stats don't lie, even if people don't believe them.

It is a very interesting topic. Let me clear something out first. I am fully onboard for autonomous cars. What trips me a bit (and probably people who are trying to find evidence against autonomous cars) is all these claims of 20 million miles. How much more experience this is compared to a regular driver. Objectively speaking this is true. But on the other hand, you Derek said it yourself - this car will probably struggle on poorly maintained roads for example. And yet, myself a driver with only 130 000 km of experience (basically a rookie compared to this car) have no problem whatsoever driving on poorly maintained road or on a dirt road.

I am software engineer and I have tried to explain the benefits of self driving cars to people and I see a very common set of misconceptions.
What people seem to struggle to understand is that computer algorithm driving a car will be MUCH better than a human in 99% of the situations. The problem is that in the remaining 1%, due to their nature, computers tend to make mistakes that seem so obvious for us humans that we apply our confirmation bias and shot down the idea.

The thing is, as you said 99% of mistakes are basically not obeying the traffic laws or getting intentionnaly or unintentionally distracted. A computer will never do that. The thing is us humans alwasy think "yeah, that will never happen to me, so I dont see the benefit for myself!". The computer being a giant calculator looking for patterns might (in 1 in a million) find a pattern where there shouldn't be and execute a maneuver that may result in an accident. This is what we see with Tesla and with virtually any other brand at some point. The car driving seemingly perfect and  just make a turn and leave the road or simply ignore a stopped vehicle and cause an accident. This is the nature of algorithms. Poorly programmed or trained model could make such a mistake. Of course a human would react like "WTF the car just made a right turn on the highway and got out of the road, a human would never make such a stupid mistake!".

Of course such a mistake would be against (probably 100 000 mistakes on the human side) making it so extremely rare that statistically it is not even worth discussing.

My point with this long comment is that sometimes in their attempt to promote their progress, companies like Waymo make a big bold statement like "we have 20 million miles of experience, much more than a human" that they provoke a reaction like "Oh yeah, 20 million miles, huh? I drove for 20 000 and I can drive on a poorly mainteined road and you cant!"

Maybe a bit more transparancy on what those numbers mean in reality and a bit more education on how things work and why they are better even though they seemingly sometimes make not the best judgements from the perspective of a human driver might push things in the right direction. A quick example is the quck sudden squeeking stop infront of the man with the cart. This kind of a stop is to be expected from a very rookie driver and even though I fully understand why such things happen, people will tend not to expect such "attitude" from someone or something that has droven 20 million miles.

To be precise: If you mean to say how do they maneuver when they get a flat at high speeds, that is something most cars have these days called traction control. Other than that the AI will just hit the brakes and pull over. Now for brake downs, For one brake downs in motion are rare but also they use redundant systems, for example, Tesla autopilot has several modules of fully functional processing units, in such a way that if one fails (say a short-circuit burns it) the other one kicks in, if it's power failure (sudden) the main systems have a backup, the battery is wired in such a way that if one section of the battery fails it Immediately jumps and starts draining a completely separate section of it. AKA another battery trough another connection to the motor and main systems. In this fashion a section of the battery module is always working as a backup for the other section, The only way it could go wrong is if both sections fail at the same time and suddenly  (which is quite probabilistically low) I do not know for sure but I can almost guarantee there is emergency break leaver or button. 20 million miles means virtually nothing when many of them occurred in Chandler which has wide, straight roads. Low traffic density. Virtually no pedestrians or animals, and sunny clear weather 350 days a year. Also, many of those miles took place in 2020 when nobody was on the road anyway. This is as close to controlled "lab conditions" as one can get, albeit still forcing the general public to participate in a technology experiment without their consent (Nuremburg has some words on that). Throw in dense traffic, high pedestrian density, snow, fog, deer, roads designed for horses with blind turns, etc and we've trained cars to self drive in the least common driving scenarios found on the planet.

I like how he talks about airplane autopilot like it's a guarantee safety feature and TOTALLY ignores Boeing and the 737 Max crashes that killed hundreds because the technology was not thoroughly tested before being deployed. This is a major problem with autonomous vehicles as a whole, a bug in the code is one thing on your smartphone, it's a wholly separate issue when it turns a two ton piece of machinery into an eradict and potentially lethal projection. It's one thing when there's a "bug" in a human but that human can be held accountable and is only responsible for their individual vehicle, it's a huge problem when that bug is instantly propogated across millions of vehicles and can't be overriden by the drivers (or they aren't expecting to need to override the systems...a stark contrast from pilots that are highly trained and paid to always be attentive). That's not even to address the cybersecurity issue, and we all know how great silicon valley is about cybersecurity.

Computers are great at being consistent, but the road is anything but consistent. Even without drivers there are too many variables from construction, to debris, to weather, to pedestrians that make the road chaotic. The sky is comparably far less complex as there's air traffic control, radar, a whole third dimension to maneuver in, and less objects to collide with as a whole. Humans on the other hand are terrible at being consistent, but fantastic at handling novel situations. That's not to say that self driving cars are a fool's errand, it's just to say that the technology is not ready for public roads and never should have been allowed (the algorithms don't even have to pass a driver's test like a 15 year old kid has too). Even experts in the industry are coming out and saying the technology is farther away than anticipated, many saying at least a decade away. Remember, we were supposed to have self driving cars by 2020 when the tech was first being hyped, and it's still in it's infancy with only one company having road trials (in the most lax regulatory state with the easiest road conditions). Even then, the cars drive erratically and get into collisions, where WAYMO refuses to disclose any contextual information about the events, and I've personally seen them constantly driving bike lanes. It seems like self driving cars might go the way of flying cars and cold fusion, a decade away, every decade.

Another issue is that they're comparing safety to the average american driver, which is a poor standard as we can pretty easily surmise that self driving cars will be replacing commercial and luxury vehicles first, two demographics that statistically are the safest drivers with millions of miles between collisions. In other words, the algorithms need to be far safer than the average driver to not LOWER average road safety in the adoption phase (these are things actuaries are already concerned about and they don't care about hype or promises, just raw data and risk).

Lastly, this all ignores a huge elephant in the room: cities designed around private individual cars, whether autonomous and electric or not, is a poor design model. Changing who and how a car drives does nothing to address the well studied problems that cities based on individual driving ALWAYS suffer more traffic, more pollution, more urban sprawl, more heat island, and more climate change problems. Technology, whether wider roads, or safer and faster cars, has never realized the promises made to sell the technology. The only things that do alleviate the problems of urban and suburban traffic are increased public mass transportation, and actively discouraging individual drivers. Imagine how bad the roads are going to be when all these autonomous vehicles are not kept in the garage but rather "rented" out with some kind of driverless Lyft service. Cars on the road could easily double as they all idle waiting for a fare, rather than sitting parked. Oh yeah, work from home is a far easier, cheaper, and faster to implement way to address the dangers of road, but it doesn't create a bunch of BS jobs to make a fundamentally flawed system appear less flawed without dramatically fixing anything (seat belts, crumple zones, and assisted driving/braking have already addressed the vast majority of the dangers of driving anyway).

I disagree that autonomous fleets in cities are going to come before autonomous cars in smaller areas. Or, at least, I _hope_ that won't happen. As you briefly glossed over towards the end, most accidents with autonomous vehicles are going to happen because other drivers mess up, and cities are precisely where there are going to be the largest concentration of potentially error-prone human drivers. An ideal situation from a safety standpoint is actually the fully-autonomous vehicles becoming more common in suburbs and slowly moving into the cities. Kudos to Waymo for the intensive testing and realizing that half-measures won't work with our stupid ape brains, though; I'm remembering Tesla putting cars on the road that _did_ , in fact, hit stationary objects, and people doing ridiculous things (even filming a porn!) in their partially-autonomous vehicles. Anyway, hopefully they're right that autonomous vehicles reduce fatalities even in the face of human error, because, to touch on your analogies, that's the _real_ reason pilots are required to be in the cockpit during takeoff and landing. Fog isn't much of an obstacle to a computer with a perfect map of the runway system and knowledge of its own x,y,z coordinates, velocity, and acceleration; however, another aircraft with no autopilot or a sudden malfunction can cause collisions without a pilot to end the landing program and move out of the way. (That's also why the elevator analogy isn't a very good one: The most complicated part of driving or piloting is maneuvering around other drivers and pilots, which isn't something an elevator operator ever had to worry about.)

You're definitely skipping over the main reason that we won't be above 50% autonomous cars in the next five or even ten years, though: Economics. In ten years, I _might_ be able to afford a ten-year-old human-driven electric car (but probably not). It'll be even longer before I can afford an autonomous car. And I'm only hovering slightly above the poverty line; there's plenty of people well into poverty who need a car to keep food on the table and a roof over their heads; and even people who are safely lower-middle class don't tend to have _new_ cars, just not-quite-as-old used cars. Most people don't have new cars, because new cars are expensive, and new cars with the latest technology features are more expensive still. The average car on the road in the US is a decade old right now (actually, 12.1, but just coming out of lockdown, the economy's still a bit out of whack, bumping the average up a bit; it was hovering in the high 11.x before that), meaning many are even older.

Also, that motorcyclist with/without a helmet scenario isn't a very good one to begin with, and whoever made the video you clipped from also misunderstood the point of such scenarios. It's actually not a question of how well the car will perform, so much as it's a question of legal liability. To demonstrate, have a much better and more realistic example: What happens when someone has been tailgating you, and then the person in front of you stops short? The car is probably capable of stopping short to avoid the car in front, causing it to get rear-ended; and it's capable of recognizing the car behind is too close and fast, thus stopping slowly and hitting the car in front. That _isn't_ an uncommon situation, unfortunately, and it's entirely due to human driver error _by other drivers_ , meaning the autonomous car may not be able to avoid it. (No, you don't get to brush that one off with "unlikely hypothetical scenarios." I have first- and secondhand experience with _exactly_ that scenario at least five times over.) The sticking point is this: Which scenario is safer for the passengers of all three cars, and should the car potentially seek to preserve its own passenger's safety, even at the expense of another vehicle's driver's life? In that scenario, I can easily imagine a situation where hitting the front car would severely injure the passenger (say, by smashing their face into the dashboard), but getting hit by the rear car would kill the driver (maybe they're not wearing a seatbelt). This is all potentially knowable by the autonomous vehicle, so what heuristic is the best one to use when you know you're going to be in court for your programming someday? Once that choice is made, who gets the blame when someone is injured, partially as the result of that decision? The programmer? The manufacturer? The vehicle's owner? The vehicle's passengers, who presumably chose the route that put it on that road? Again, it's a question of liability, one that should probably be figured out now, but one which, given the way our courts run on precedent, probably won't actually be figured out until it actually happens. However, anyone who uses those scenarios to _criticize_ autonomous vehicles has a fundamental misunderstanding of what the problem actually is.

I recently got a nice (used) Toyota sienna with laser powered cruise control, and it is the nicest cruise control I have ever had. No other car I have ever owned has been capable of performing as well, and the controls are all on a single gamer-friendly knob, instead of random buttons I have to read every time.

That said, it's from 05, it doesn't know how to do calculus to know when to stop accelerating. If it sees it is going more than 5 mph different than what you set it, it up shifts, sometimes twice, and then it'll shoot past it's target, sometimes even into detection range of another car, then slowing way down, it doesn't know how to solve for time of acceleration, it's really obvious.

But, if you get it up to the correct speed manually, it maintains that speed WAY better than a foot-powered foot ever could, so in that way, I use it as a manual throttle lock, instead of a real cruise control. I'm always attentive of it, because even with car detection, it doesn't work great driving into the sun, or driving in the rain. Additionally, on the highway it has no idea about lanes, and I have to physically pause it, or switch lanes before it tries to slow me down when I pass.

Are self driving cars better than that? Yeah, even a shitty Tesla like what electroboom has can lane switch, but it has obvious failure modes too. Maybe that's because it's not "grade four driverless" or whatever, but ultimately I won't ever drive a car that I can't be in control of, because the car is a tool for me to use, not a chauffeur.

Cruise is a tool. ABS is a tool. Sonar range finders are a *tool* and when driverless becomes a thing, I will still use it as a tool. Even if I don't have to have my hands on the wheel, it *will not* be better at prediction and physics than me, only at multitasking and long distance sign reading (curse my nearsighted genes!) And reactions as well, but if it hasn't identified the problem correctly then it doesn't matter if it's reaction is .0001 seconds, because I'll have to take over in .01 seconds anyway.

An average or above average driver will be better than a computer at solving for edge cases. A bottom 25% driver may as well switch to driverless in 15 years when they're actually affordable.

I don't like how this is a sponsored video. The problem isn't that there is a sponsor, that's fine, the problem is that the scientific approach that is typically yours, where questions are asked and an answer is searched for, at least feels compromised. You sound like you're saying what the sponsor wants us to hear, but wrapping it in a veneer of sciency stuff. Except many of the arguments made ring hollow or inaccurate. There are many problems with autonomous vehicles, and you only show the viewpoint of the sponsor, which is in no position to make an objective assessment, and we know it.

Modern AI is arguably not learning anything, just memorizing an immense library of patterns. We do not have any feasibly ability to audit the source code of the self-driving vehicles because there essentially isn't any, just an impossible to untangle mess of various learned models taped together, with a bunch of layers. Anyone who worked in software knows how things can get really ugly really fast in the real world, even when humans know what the software is meant to do and how it's designed, and from what little has transpired out of companies like Tesla, we know their software efforts do not exist on some ethereal plane of existence where the typical problems don't apply.

Those vehicles are trained in often unrealistic scenarios: only on simple, wide, straight american (st)roads, or only in clear weather conditions, or with training data with "exceptional" events culled away for easier training. You make the analogy to elevators and airplanes, but really that's silly, because those are effectively on rails, much like trains. Cars are _not_ trains and roads at _not_ rails. The possibility space is much smaller, and there is no complex reading of human behavior required to insert in elevator or air corridor traffic. On a road, you come into much closer contact, at much faster speeds, with other agents, who are very hard to predict and to read, even for humans sometimes. Simply playing it safe and avoiding the hard situations will not work in the real world, and neither will deferring to a driver who was told they could relax. Asking for an overnight transition is even less.

Context is impossible for self-driving cars to understand: a suicidal person walking towards the road with bad intentions, kids playing on the side, people having a bbq, or whatever context where people are in line of sight for the car, are impossible to distinguish for an AI, it will just see people near the road. Because of that, the car will be tuned to react overly confident, or underconfident, or likely both. How does a driverless car react to other dangerous drivers attempting road-rage manoeuver ? Yes it won't get "angry", but it can still very likely get outside of comfortable operation conditions and be put in a situation it wasn't trained on. What about learner drivers ? Intoxicated drivers ? Someone having a stroke ? A mechanical failure ?

A human does need training to react to every possible scenario, because it has a _brain_ and understands what it is doing. What humans are trash at is boring driving conditions and boring everyday commutes where people are effectively driving in autopilot mode themselves, not fully aware of the situation. This is where driving aids come into their own, and can augment the driver awareness. This is desirable. What I'm less sure about is leaving that sweet spot for systems that involve the human so little it completely loses any involvement, because then the human insight into context is lost to the vehicle.

The next part is this tech is exploitable. Adversarial attacks on those networks are not a new thing, and that's before you get in the actual infosec security issues of having fully drive-by-wire cars with network connectivity to the drivetrain. You'd be hard pressed to find _any_ security researcher who's honestly _not_ nervous about safety-critical closed-source systems connected to the internet, let alone who would trust one with his own life.

Lastly I don't like what this means in a world were all cars are autonomous. This tech isn't free, it is owned by some of the biggest conglomerates who already have a dangerous level of control over our lives. In a future where only autonomous cars are allowed, and where we no longer own our cars, we are now tributary of the whims of that corporation for getting around. Losing your google account is bad enough today, but tomorrow it could mean you can get stranded. Or it could mean a cartel could own the pricing for transportation and artificially raise it for profit maximization. We've seen how that does wonders already in plenty of areas in tech. Forfeiting the privilege of driving to machines means losing it to a couple dozen companies, who will exert total control on who is allowed on the roads, which were supposed to be public infrastructure.

Is human freedom worth loss of life ? Now you have some real questions to discuss, and historically the answer has been a big fat "it's complicated".

It's strange to talk about autonomous driving without even mentioning Tesla FSD. True, they don't have fully autonomous vehicles regularly travelling without drivers, but they are taking on a much harder problem than Waymo. It's also strange to talk about Waymo autonomous driving without mentioning their main drawback, which is that they rely on externally generated maps and cannot function in an unmapped area (or, indeed, in a mapped area that has significantly changed since the mapping). Waymo has 20 million miles experience, which sounds impressive, but Tesla has data from at least 10 billion miles of regular car driving. Tesla FSD works on unmapped streets. And yes, I mean "works" - it still requires constant driver supervision, but though it still has some kinks that need intervention, it is very, very close and frequently can travel for half an hour and more in city streets with no intervention. Sorry, but Derek is way too optimistic here.

Lidar only works in good weather conditions (e.g. heavy fog or water spray from cars in front is deadly), same for cameras. And those ranges of 300m for lidar and 500m for camera sound absolutely unbelievable! Like, pick any sign on a local road, walk 500m away, take a picture and then try to read the sign in the image. You won't. Typical ranges one talks about when using cameras in autonomous driving are like 100-150m max.

Also, you see at least 4 Lidar-Sensors mounted on the car in the video. Has anyone thought about the cost? The 360¬∞ one on top is at least 30,000$, the others probably like half of that each. On top of that you have the 28(!) cameras (some of them with expensive lenses, if they are supposed to come even close to what is claimed) and several radar sensors. The latter typically cost about 1,500$ each. In sum this means that just the sensor equipment costs more than most normal cars! How is this supposed to go into a mass-produced consumer product?

Last point I want to make: energy consumption. With electric cars we are already talking about their comparably low driving range. All of these sensors and especially the GPUs/TPUs and processors needed to make use of the data need a lot, and I really mean *a lot*,  of power. This doesn't go well together at all.
(Before anyone mentions Tesla: They have never used close to this many sensors or had such a high level of automation. And there is a reason why they recently announced that they will exclusively rely on cameras in the future.)

Overall, I must say that this video feels like a big (false) advertisement to me, as harsh as that may sound. Not for Waymo specifically, but autonomous cars in general. Maybe Derek is just a tad too excited about them?

Self-driving cars are going to make a huge positive difference in the world, sooner than most people think, and every day we wait is a lot of damage, pain, and death. Obviously we shouldn't rush things inappropriately, we should make sure each system is significantly better than the average human (with data to prove it) before allowing wide launch, but to wait for perfection is tantamount to murder.

I'm not sure who will get self driving solved first, but I'm glad that there are multiple groups of skilled and dedicated people working on it. I don't know if Waymo's approach of high definition maps with lidar and a team that looks like it has more people than cars will win out, or if Tesla's larger fleet, collecting data from the wild, and using primarily vision (I think they still have ultrasonic sensors, but they've dropped radar and never had lidar) will get there faster. I think either approach can work to be honest.

I'm not convinced that almost full-self driving cars are more dangerous though, even if people pay less attention because they are overconfident. People already pay less attention than we should when driving. The question is whether the probability of a near full self driving car crashing while the pilot isn't paying attention is greater or less than the probability of a non-self driving car crashing while the driver isn't paying attention. Depending on how reliable the self driving system on the car is, the degree to which the pilot has to not pay attention to exceed the non self driving baseline varies greatly. For example, if you just have lane keeping assistance, taking your eyes off the road for even a few seconds is extremely dangerous, if you have Tesla fsd beta (v9 is most up to date right now I think), you are pretty unlikely to have an accident in a few seconds of inattention, even though you should keep paying attention throughout. We don't have good external data on any of these fsd systems (at least none that I've been able to find), but I suspect that people trust it less than they trust themselves when driving, and as a result even partially self driving systems are safer, with the twist that people who have more experience and therefore more trust in the system they use are less attentive and slightly more likely to be in an accident than new users, but still overall less likely to be in a collision than an unassisted driver. I'd really like to see better data on this.

I personally don't mind the idea of driverless cars themselves. But depending on how strictly they follow road regulations and what their normal behavior is, I could see human drivers getting frustrated or driving erratically, and producing some very unusual edge-case situations. Which is what questions like the motorcyclists explore, that delve into really interesting (and sometimes unrealistic) moral dilemmas and conclusions. I also think that driverless cars, in a way, are really just another form of public transportation, depending on how they're implemented - though what many cities and countries have currently could certainly be adopted more effectively in the states, as other people have pointed out.

But beyond that, there are A LOT of questions that went unanswered in this video. Starting with the technology, LiDAR is already well documented to be a significant health risk to people's (and animals')eyes, in a world where we already have an enormous amount of radio wave transmissions. Sure, Google only has a handful of cars out right now, but if, say, a tenth of the vehicles on the road are driverless and rely on LiDAR for a significant portion of their information about the outside world,  what will that do to the general population? And there are ethical questions as well. Google is already renowned for being incredibly intrusive and selling user data - what's to say they wouldn't use information from their cars, too?
I'm aware that TESLA is utilizing very different technology for their driverless features. There are just a lot of things worth considering when there's any sort of automation like this - what's the technology that you put into it? What are the risks? And what are the alternatives? And how exploitable is it?

I'm a software tester. I have serious doubts about the industry's code deployment processes, given their move-fast-and-break-things mindset and ideological hatred of regulators -- this is especially true of Tesla. If Waymo makes a software change, how is it tested (virtually and on real streets) before it's deployed to their vehicles? How frequently are those updates made? What regulations is the company willing to accept to ensure that catastrophic bugs don't make it onto the streets? The millions of miles of real-world driving with minimal accidents are great, but how many iterations of the software does that cover? And critically, what weather conditions/traffic density/road-map/etc scenarios do those tests cover? By starting in Arizona, they've chosen the friendliest possible environment and many challenges lay ahead. 

I hate driving, but I agree that people are horrendous drivers who should be torn from the wheel as soon as is practicable. But, I'm deeply skeptical of my industry's ability to deliver and maintain life-saving and -threatening code -- easy enough in the short term, but incredibly difficult long term as teams get bored once a problem is "solved". High-skilled engineers want to run off and work on something new. Management starts squeezing the development teams to do more with less and faster in order to boost their margins, etc. Strong regulation slows things down and adds cost, but it can save lives in the long run.

"There are no solutions, only tradeoffs" applies to driving safety here as well. While true that self-driving cars can't make "human error" mistakes (as 8:42 states), these are traded-off for different systematic errors: distraction and rule-breaking get traded out for sensor failure and uncaught corner cases in the software. Overall I personally think this tradeoff will indeed result in fewer total fatalities, so Derek's streamlining this nuance out to strengthen his case is understandable. But making the case, as Derek implies here, that "automated driving is 100% safe" is vulnerable to anecdotal counter-example (e.g. Tesla's failure to detect a white semi-truck in plain daylight) in a way that "automated driving has a set of fatal errors smaller than human drivers" doesn't (even if it is less succinct).

I'm somewhat disappointed by the video and found it to be a very simplistic take, as well as very american-centric. A lot of the video was dedicated toward human attitudes and behaviour regarding self driving cars, while very little was focussed on technology readiness. Eg. how will the cars handle it if EVERY car is fitted with LIDAR? Surrounded by 100 cars each with multiple LIDARs will it still function or be rendered useless, perhaps something in between with phantom detections?

There was so much nuance that was either brushed over or ignored, attributing poor performance to such throwaway comments as, "in some parts of the world the roads aren't well enough maintained." Meanwhile you're driving round in perfect conditions on very wide American style roads, many of which are dual carriageways. Try that Waymo car on a narrow country road in the UK and see how it does, my bet is that it would cross the lane divider frequently just as Tesla's do too. Self driving cars that are trained on very wide american roads are actually dangerous and not fit for purpose on narrower UK and European roads. They also seem to be averse at making strong control inputs, which means that tight turns and corners are an issue for them, but again not a problem on wide roads with sweeping turns, and all intersections meet at 90 degrees.

I'm not a luddite, and I of course accept that in certain conditions and on certain types of road (essentially dual carriageways and motorways), they are undoubtedly better drivers and never suffer lapses in concentration. However I have not seen anything to suggest that any self driving tech has even come close to driving safely on smaller and more congested roads.

With regards to your poll at 1:20 these options are not mutually exclusive, I am both excited to see a future where they exist and function well, but at the same time I still think it will be >10 years before full unmonitored self-driving is ready.

So, on perfect roads with ideal weather, it works.  (Presumably they've fixed the driving into the side of the bus thing, I'll assume that for the moment.). But the problem isn't making it work 99% of the time.  It's the 1%...the long tail.

- a sudden downpour in which visibility drops to nearly nil in seconds (what do you do if moving?)
- a construction zone where the old lines have been blacked out, and new ones placed, but at an angle, reflection off both old and new make them look similar, and suddenly it's not clear where the lines are
- a flash flood (happened a few miles down the highway from where I'm sitting)
- whiteout from blowing snow
- 1000 other such things

Judgment, and the ability to improvise, rather than 1000 years of driving history, is a major way to deal with these.

I got enthusiastic about self drive when DARPA stopped holding self drive challenges because the technology was too good...no longer an advanced research topic, in their view, apparently.  And when Google (pre Waymo) published a video of their vehicle sitting things that humans didn't.

You're at what level of driving?) or driving into the side of a tractor trailer when sunlight blinded.

It'll take more than a drive on a nice day on multi lane roads to convince me.  Show me it driving in a sudden squall, with children piling out of a school, poor lighting, driven rain making the lidar picture more complicated, shopping bags blowing down the street, and maybe a homework assignment amongst those.  Nice day driving may mean that they're one percent of the way there.

Generally love this channel but a lot was missed here. A lot was made of the number of miles driven, but little was made about how quickly AI can learn relative to humans. Humans don't need millions of miles to understand the context around them. They just need a few thousand at most. There weren't any really hard intersections, blind corners, wet roads, or what AI people call "edge cases" here. A lot can be said on this. Tesla has perhaps some of the best data on drivers, and granted they don't use LIDAR, but the latest version shows what the machine can see, which certainly seems good enough (e.g., LIDAR can see a stop sign 500m away, but how useful is that information for the car - probably not that useful at all). But a few videos of their system in much more complex scenarios shows how quickly the system fails to perform.

Also, the study quoted here says 6.1 million miles of driving with 18 "incidents". Looking at the average data for the US, there are about 2.6 deaths per billion miles driven. There are also about 100x as many accidents as deaths (based on my searching). Assuming my math is correct, you can estimate that over the same 6.1 million miles, you would only expect 2.1 crashes that damage property. That's quite a bit less. And explaining away some of the incidents as due to other human error doesn't get around the issue, because a) AI cars need to drive with humans, b) those are likely those "edge cases" where humans often know how to react without an incident, and c) the human crash statistics include "other driver error" as well.

Finally, you didn't at all get into the problems of security with things like hacking or purposeful modification of signage to confuse AI systems (which are often labelled as "brittle" to such changes). There's just so much that could go wrong. Generally, this channel shows a lot of the picture, but on this topic there's so much missing from this message.

So, are these cars currently better than the average human? I think there's very good reason to doubt that assertion.

Still, we have to contend with how driverless technology interacts *with* human error. Predicting something slow like a pedestrian isn't terribly hard but fast moving objects like bad drivers in cars or trucks, or even reckless bikers or PEVs are significantly harder to understand. Until human drivers are banned and everyone has access to driverless road vehicles, a human knows how to deal with stupid humans better than a law following AI

We also have to wonder why Tesla is so absolutely garbage at driverless tech when Google has gotten this far. Think it might really be a sign that it's time for Tesla to hand off everything it does to someone else

Read and did a bit of math:
In the US over 3 Trillion miles are driven each year. Approximately 6 million car accidents (of any kind, most are harmless and won‚Äôt even cause significant property damage) happen in that same time frame. So per million miles driven there are approximately 2 accidents.

Waymo with their 20 million miles driven and only 18 accidents, is just below 1 accident per million miles. Or about twice as safe as a human driver. This is also before you account for the fact that the US average includes things like truck drivers driving hundreds of miles a day on the same lonely back highways of the Western US where you barely encounter any cars and thus are incredibly unlikely to crash lowering the collision average significantly compared to urban and suburban areas where Waymo does most of their driving.

So in terms of capabilities I would definitely say we‚Äôre here in terms of self-driving.

Also as a note: Telsa‚Äôs seld-driving options are at most a 2-3 (for regulation purposes they are a 2) on the self-driving scale provided, essentially they are currently more akin to early Waymo examples of people being responsible for the driving and needing to assist the car from time to time, but leaving too much up to the car and getting distracted. So if you have a Tesla, and want to use the feature, keep your eyes on the road.

This video seemed very American-centric to me, which does make sense since he's American, but I'd like to give a European perspective on self-driving cars

The way I see it, self-driving cars are the solution to a strictly American problem. The problem of 'what if I want to go somewhere, but don't want to drive?'. Where I live, in the Netherlands, we have many more options for transport than cars. We can of course cycle there, walk there, take the bus, take the train, or any combination of those to get to our destination. We don't have a desire for self-driving cars because that's essentially what our public transport does for us. 

The self-driving car isn't the *only* solution to traffic accidents, either. Getting people off the road and onto public transport is a solution, for one, but road design also plays a huge part in how drivers act. The wide, straight roads (or stroads, as they're called) you see in America do the exact opposite of create a driver-friendly environment, as they only instigate people to drive faster.

Another point to me is that self-driving cars would absolutely not work here in the Netherlands. I see a lot of American roads that are wide, give a lot of space and vision for cars, and are generally convenient to navigate,. Those are much less common here. We have lots of roads where cyclists, pedestrians, and cars all go on the same narrow, low-vision roads. Drivers have to make a lot of complicated decisions and manoeuvrers like getting out of the way onto the pavement to make space for an oncoming car, or judging whether or not you have the time and space to pass a group of cyclists. I'm not it's impossible, but for an AI to pass these problems it would practically need to have human level intelligence.

Everyone getting in their own self-driving car to their destination is like the Tesla tunnel to me. Instead of everyone getting in a separate one-person vehicle, it could've simply been a subway that packs hundreds of times the amount of passengers per hour at a much better energy efficiency. 

All in all, self-driving cars don't look like a solution to me. Safer, yes, but not the solution to traffic or travel time or walkability or lack of public transport. They look more like a band-aid fix that only distract from the real problem of car-centric city design

As someone with some experience in the field I can confirm that there are multiple companies that already have much better than human autopilot under good driving conditions. The main problems I've seen in the field are older car companies not understanding how to develop software in general and newer companies that overestimate the results that their NN-based solutions get. In both cases you end up with an autopilot that would occasionally catastrophically fail. Waymo knows how to develop software and the hardware they use is complete overkill so it is very expensive but at least guarantees a minimum level of safety. And a lot of it comes down to using the ridiculously expensive but also very reliable LIDAR. Tesla's solution is entirely based on NNs processing camera images which doesn't give you this baseline safety and you can see it in their accidents. The autopilot often fails in trivial situations due to the limitations of NNs. Their whole concept is based on doing what the human brain does but they've skipped the step where the human brain uses simple and hard-wired algorithms to generate 3D data from the two "cameras" we have. A fully autonomous car can be made entirely using cameras but not without simpler and more predictable perception algorithms compared to what Tesla are doing. You don't necessarily need LIDAR, though cheaper LIDAR would be warmly welcomed. And you have to keep in mind that a solution that would lead to most cars on the road being autonomous would mean that the autopilot shouldn't add too much cost to the total cost of the vehicle. And I would say $2000 is a good approximation of this limit. A LIDAR or NN heavy solution cannot get even close to this limit.

TL.DR. Imo we have the technology to easily and cheaply do it, but we are limited by the human error of the people managing these projects.

20 Million miles of data is about a third of what Tesla's cars collect every single day.  (1 million cars x 60 miles per day, average).  Those "simulated" miles are extremely dubious.  Who verifies that what the simulation does is realistic?  Consider a deer crossing the road ahead of you, at night.  How many deer interactions are there in 20 million miles of real world data?   I'd guess maybe a few hundred - but deer interactions are complicated.  How the deer reacts depends not just on it's own desires - but also on the time of day, time of year, the weather, whether there are other cars coming from a different direction, your speed, whether there are baby deer with it's momma, whether it's the rutting season...stuff we can't even imagine.   You simply cannot capture enough deer encounters with 20 million miles of real world data to safely infer what a deer might do - and what your best course of action is.  So you're left with simulation trying to fill in these gaps.   But the behavior of deer is not something that WayMo's simulation engineers know....they just don't.   Sure, you could get a deer biologist "expert" to come in and work on that part - but do THEY even know?   I think not.   But Tesla now have somewhere around 70 BILLION miles of real-world data.  And that's going to include a thousand times more deer encounters than WayMo's dataset.  (Actually, a hell of a lot more than that because WayMo's cars only drive in city centers).   This is the fundamental flaw in WayMo's approach.  Sure, they can capture enough in-town data to build a reasonably safe car - and with only a few hundred cars on the roads, the odds of them encountering something they never saw before is small.  But when you have a few million cars driving on country roads, freeways, in tunnels, in different countries where the rules and driving customs are different - they simply CANNOT capture enough data to do the job.   So, yeah - a WayMo taxi can drive you around some small downtown area - but ask it to drive you from El Paso, Texas to Sheboygan Wisconsin  (as my Tesla recently drove me) - it's going to see VASTLY  more things than they have data for...and they can't fix that.  They'd need a million cars on the road (which WayMo can't afford) - each one covered in their sensors (which are EXPENSIVE - so they won't pursuade large car makers to install them unnecessarily for a few years before the software will work).   This is a serious problem - and I don't see how anyone other than a large car maker with the motivation to spend the money on it can possibly make this work...outside of some tiny, heavily constrained area.

Or at least every kind of road and weather experienced in the region in which the car is sold.  It might be that a car manufactured for the US market couldn't recognize the camels and kangaroos found in Australia and would simply refuse to self-drive if moved outside of North America...until Tesla had enough miles of driving in Australia to extend the AI's capabilities.
